|3.4{{e|2}}
|}

On 27 March, TEPCO reported stagnant water in the basement of unit 2 (inside the reactor/turbine building complex, but outside the primary containment) was measured at 1000&nbsp;mSv/h or more, which prompted evacuation. The exact dose rate remains unknown as the technicians fled the place after their first measurement went off-scale. Additional basement and trench-area measurements indicated 60&nbsp;mSv/h in unit 1, "over 1000"&nbsp;mSv/h<ref name=TEPCO28/> in unit 2, and 750&nbsp;mSv/h in unit 3. The report indicated the main source was iodine-134<ref name=HNK27>{{cite web|url=http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/27_12.html|title=Extreme radiation detected at No.2 reactor|date=27 March 2011|work=HNK}}</ref> with a half-life of less than an hour, which resulted in a radioactive iodine concentration 10&nbsp;million times the normal value in the reactor.<ref name=Reuters26/>  TEPCO later retracted its report, stating that the measurements were inaccurate and attributed the error to comparing the isotope responsible, [[isotopes of iodine|iodine-134]], to normal levels of another isotope.<ref name=WNN27/> Measurements were then corrected, stating that the iodine levels were 100,000 times the normal level.<ref>http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/mar/27/japan-nuclear-error-radiation-reading</ref> On 28 March, the erroneous radiation measurement caused TEPCO to reevaluate the software used in analysis.<ref>[http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/01_28.html Program errors force TEPCO to review all data]</ref>

Measurements within the reactor/turbine buildings, but not in the basement and trench areas, were made on 18 April.<ref name="ReferenceA">http://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/19/world/asia/19japan.html Radiation Levels a Bar to New Plan for Japanese Nuclear Plant</ref> These robotic measurements indicated up to 49&nbsp;mSv/h in unit 1 and 57&nbsp;mSv/h in unit 3.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> This is substantially lower than the basement and trench readings, but still exceeds safe working levels without constant worker rotation.<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref>[http://www.asahi.com/english/TKY201104190209.html Editorial: TEPCO must prepare for additional risks in taming Fukushima crisis]</ref> Inside primary containment, levels are much higher.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

By 23 March 2011, neutron radiation had been observed outside the reactors 13 times at the Fukushima I site. While this could indicate ongoing [[nuclear fission|fission]], a [[criticality accident|recriticality event]] was not believed to account for these readings.<ref>'''Neutron beam observed 13 times at crippled Fukushima nuke plant''' TOKYO, 23 March, Kyodo News http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2011/03/80539.html</ref> Based on those readings and TEPCO reports of high levels of chlorine-38, Dr. Ferenc Dalnoki-Veress speculated that transient criticalities may have occurred. However, Edwin Lyman at the Union of Concerned Scientists was skeptical, believing the reports of chlorine-38 to be in error.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ecocentric.blogs.time.com/2011/03/30/has-fukushimas-reactor-no-1-gone-critical/ |title=Has Fukushima's Reactor No. 1 Gone Critical? |work=Ecocentric |date=30 March 2011 |accessdate=1 April 2011 }}</ref> TEPCO's chlorine-38 report was later retracted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-21/tepco-retracts-chlorine-arsenic-findings-at-fukushima-station.html |title=Tepco Retracts Chlorine, Arsenic Findings at Fukushima Station |publisher=Bloomberg News |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=29 April 2011 |first=Tsuyoshi |last=Inajima}}</ref> Noting that limited, uncontrolled chain reactions might occur at Fukushima I, a spokesman for the International Atomic Energy Agency ([[IAEA]]) "emphasized that the nuclear reactors won<U+2019>t explode."<ref>Fukushima Workers Threatened by Heat Bursts; Sea Radiation Rises By Jonathan Tirone, Sachiko Sakamaki and Yuriy Humber Mar/31/2011 http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/record-high-levels-of-radiation-found-in-sea-near-crippled-nuclear-reactor.html</ref>

On 15 April, TEPCO reported that nuclear fuel had melted and fallen to the lower containment sections of three of the [[Fukushima I]] reactors, including reactor three. The melted material was not expected to breach one of the lower containers, causing a serious radiation release. Instead, the melted fuel was thought to have dispersed uniformly across the lower portions of the containers of reactors No. 1, No. 2 and No. 3, making the resumption of the fission process, known as a "recriticality," most unlikely.<ref>[http://www.globalsecuritynewswire.org/gsn/nw_20110415_5020.php ''Japan Plant Fuel Melted Partway Through Reactors: Report''], Friday, 15 April 2011</ref>

On 19 April, TEPCO estimated that the unit-2 turbine basement contained 25,000 cubic meters of contaminated water.<ref name="TEPCOTransfer">{{cite web |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110419e2.pdf |title=Transfer to the Process Main Building |publisher=TEPCO |date=19 April 2011 |accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref> The water was measured to have 3 MBq/cm3 of Cs-137 and 13 MBq/cm3 of I-131: TEPCO characterized this level of contamination as "extremely high."<ref name="TEPCOTransfer" /> To attempt to prevent leakage to the sea, TEPCO planned to pump the water from the basement to the Centralized Radiation Waste Treatment Facility.<ref name="TEPCOTransfer" />

A suspected hole from the melting of fuel in unit 1 has allowed water to leak in an unknown path from unit 1<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/13_03.html |title=No.1 reactor is in a "meltdown" state |publisher=NHK |date=13 May 2011 |accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kubota |first=Yoko |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/12/us-japan-nuclear-reactor-idUSTRE74B1H520110512 |title=Fukushima reactor has a hole, leading to leakage |publisher=Reuters.com |date= |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> which has exhibited radiation measurements "as high as 1,120 mSv/h."<ref>{{cite web|last=Inajima |first=Tsuyoshi |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-27/tokyo-water-radiation-falls-to-zero-for-first-time-since-crisis.html |title=Radiation Readings in Fukushima Reactor Rise to Highest Since Crisis Began |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date= |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2011/05/89922.html Fukushima's No. 1 reactor building radiation up to 700 millisieverts]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref> Radiation measurements of the water in the unit-3 spent-fuel pool were reported at 140 kBq of radioactive caesium-134 per cubic centimeter, 150 kBq of caesium-137 per cubic centimeter, and 11 kBq per cubic centimeter of iodine-131 on 10 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/10_30.html |title=Radiation high at No.3 reactor pool |publisher=NHK |date=10 May 2011 |accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref>

In August 2011, several areas were spotted inside the reactor buildings where dose rates reach several sieverts per hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enenews.com/fukushima-plant-worker-higher-10000-millisieverthr-many-spots-reactor-buildings-1-2-3 |title=Fukushima plant worker: even higher than 10,000 millisieverts/hr at many spots in reactor buildings 1, 2 and 3 |publisher=Enenews.com |date= |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref>

===Site contamination===

====Soil====
TEPCO have reported at three sites 500 meters from the reactors that the caesium-134 and caesium-137 levels in the soil are between 7.1 kBq and 530 kBq per kilo of undried soil.<ref>http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110713e15.pdf</ref> 

[[File:Chernboyl vs Fukuashima2.png|thumb|right|The Fukushima soil contamination compared with the Chernobyl release for a series of key isotopes. The two data sets have been adjusted to make the caesium-137 bars the same size to allow the isotope signatures to be compared with ease]]

Small traces of plutonium have been found in the soil near the stricken reactors: repeated examinations of the soil suggest that the plutonium level is similar to the background level caused by atomic bomb tests.<ref>http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110713e14.pdf</ref> As the isotope signature of the plutonium is closer to that of power-reactor plutonium, TEPCO suggested that "two samples out of five may be the direct result of the recent incident."<ref>http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11032812-e.html Press Release (28 Mar 2011).
Detection of radioactive material in the soil in Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Station</ref> The more important thing to look at is the [[curium]] level in the soil;<ref>http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110713e17.pdf</ref> the soil does contain a short-lived isotope (curium-242) which shows that some [[alpha]] emitters have been released in small amounts by the accident. The release of the beta/gamma emitters such as caesium-137 has been far greater. In the short and medium term the effects of the iodine and the caesium release will dominate the effect of the accident on farming and the general public. In common with almost all soils, the soil at the reactor site contains [[uranium]], but the concentration of uranium and the isotope signature<ref>http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110713e16.pdf</ref> suggests that the uranium is the normal, natural uranium in the soil.

Radioactive strontium-89 and strontium-90 were discovered in soil at the plant on 18 April, amounts detected in soil one-half kilometer from the facility ranging from 3.4 to 4400 Bq/kg of dry soil.<ref name="NHKStrontium" /><ref name="TEPCOStrontium" /><ref name="TEPCOStrontiumSea" />  Strontium remains in soil from above-ground nuclear testing; however, the amounts measured at the facility are approximately 130 times greater than the amount typically associated with previous nuclear testing.<ref name="NHKStrontium" /><ref name="TEPCOStrontiumSea" />

The isotope signature of the release looks very different to that of the Chernobyl accident:<ref>{{cite web|author=Name (required) |url=http://markforeman.wordpress.com/2011/06/03/more-isotope-data-from-japan/ |title=More isotope data from Japan <U+00AB> Mark Foreman's Blog |publisher=Markforeman.wordpress.com |date=3 June 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref><ref>http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110708e16.pdf</ref> the Japanese accident has released much less of the involatile plutonium, minor actinides and fission products than Chernobyl did.

On 31 March, TEPCO reported that it had measured radioactivity in the plant-site groundwater which was 10,000 times the government limit. The company did not think that this radiation had spread to drinking water.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2011-04-01-japanquake01_ST_N.htm | title=Nuclear crisis puts evacuation zones under scrutiny | accessdate=2 April 2011 | author=Rubin, Rita | date=1 April 2011 |work=USA Today}}</ref> NISA questioned the radioactivity measurement and TEPCO is re-evaluating it.<ref name="JapanTimesApr1">{{cite web | url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20110401x1.html | title=Iodine 131 found in groundwater | accessdate=3 April 2011 | author=Ito, Masami | date=1 April 2011 | work=The Japan Times Online}}</ref> Some debris around the plant has been found to be highly radioactive, including a concrete fragment emanating 900&nbsp;mSv/h.<ref>http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/24_01.html TEPCO: Highly radioactive concrete fragment found{{Dead link |date=May 2011}}</ref>

====Air and direct radiation====
Air outside, but near, unit 3 was reported at 70&nbsp;mSv/h on 26 April.<ref name="AsahiHighRad">{{cite web |url=http://www.asahi.com/english/TKY201104250130.html |title=High radiation levels detected at Fukushima grounds a month after explosions |work=Asahi Shimbun |location=Japan |date=26 April 2011 |accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref> This was down from radiation levels as high as 130&nbsp;mSv/h near units 1 and 3 in late March.<ref name="AsahiHighRad" /> Removal of debris reduced the radiation measurements from localized highs of up to 900&nbsp;mSv/h to less than 100&nbsp;mSv/h at all exterior locations near the reactors; however, readings of 160&nbsp;mSv/h were still measured at the waste-treatment facility.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Yomiuri Shimbun |url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T110425003601.htm |title=Map details radiation at N-plant site |publisher=Yomiuri.co.jp |date=26 April 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref>

===Discharge to seawater and contaminated sealife===
Results revealed on 22 March from a sample taken by TEPCO about 100 m south of the discharge channel of units 1<U+2013>4 showed elevated levels of Cs-137, [[Caesium-134|caesium-134 (Cs-134)]] and I-131.<ref name=WNN22/> A sample of seawater taken on 22 March 330m south of the discharge channel (30 kilometers off the coastline) had elevated levels of I-131 and Cs-137. Also, north of the plant elevated levels of these isotopes were found on 22 March (as well as Cs-134, [[tellurium-129]] and tellurium-129m (Te-129m)), although the levels were lower.<ref name=WNN24/> Samples taken on 23 and/or 24 March contained about 80&nbsp;Bq/mL of iodine-131 (1850 times the statutory limit) and 26&nbsp;Bq/mL and caesium-137, most likely caused by atmospheric deposition.<ref name=IAEAiodine/> By 26 and 27 March this level had decreased to 50&nbsp;Bq/mL (11)<ref name=tepco28/> iodine-131 and 7&nbsp;Bq/mL (2.9)<ref name=tepco28/> caesium-137 (80 times the limit).<ref name=tepcobetu11>{{cite web|url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110326e1.pdf|title=The result of the nuclide analysis of the seawater around the discharge canal (south) of Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Station|work=TEPCO|date=26 March 2011}}</ref> Hidehiko Nishiyama, a senior NISA official, stated that radionuclide contamination would "be very diluted by the time it gets consumed by fish and seaweed."<ref name=Reuters26/> Above the seawater, IAEA reported "consistently low" dose rates of 0.04<U+2013>0.1&nbsp;<U+03BC>Sv/h on 27 March.

By 29 March iodine-131 levels in seawater 330 m south of a key discharge outlet had reached 138&nbsp;Bq/ml (3,355 times the legal limit),<ref name="asahi.com"/><ref name="www3.nhk.or.jp"/> and by 30 March, iodine-131 concentrations had reached 180&nbsp;Bq/ml at the same location near the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear plant, 4,385 times the legal limit.<ref name="www3.nhk.or.jp"/><ref name="www3.nhk.or.jp"/> The high levels could be linked to a feared overflow of highly radioactive water that appeared to have leaked from the unit -2 turbine building.<ref name="online.wsj.com"/> On 15 April, I-131 radiation levels were 6,500 times the legal limits.<ref name="nytimes.com"/> On 16 April, TEPCO began dumping zeolite, a mineral "that absorbs radioactive substances, aiming to slow down contamination of the ocean."<ref>[http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20110416/wl_asia_afp/japandisasteraccidentnuclearmineral Japan's TEPCO tips radiation-sucking mineral in sea]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref>

: Seawater radionuclide concentration on 29 March 2011:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110330e10.pdf |title=The result of the nuclide analysis of the seawater |accessdate=30 March 2011 }}</ref>
