File:Fukushima I Accidents Tochigi Iod-131 tap water contamination.png|Tochigi Prefecture
File:Fukushima I Accidents Tokyo Iod-131 tap water contamination.png|Tokyo Prefecture
</gallery>

On 2 July samples of tapwater taken in Tokyo Shinjuku ward radioactive caesium-137 was detected for the first time since April. The concentration was 0.14 becquerel per kilogram and none was discovered yesterday, which compares with 0.21 becquerel on 22 April, according to the Tokyo Metropolitan Institute of Public Health. No caesium-134 or iodine-131 was detected. The level was below the safety limit set by the government. "This is unlikely to be the result of new radioactive materials being introduced, because no other elements were detected, especially the more sensitive iodine", into the water supply, were the comments of Hironobu Unesaki, a nuclear engineering professor at Kyoto University.<ref>''sfgate'' (4 July 2011) [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2011/07/03/bloomberg1376-LNS8HU1A1I4H01-0NUT9KC0HS2K9NJAM17MPAO2OS.DTL  Cesium-137 found in tapwater Tokyo]</ref>

====Breast milk====
Small amounts of radioactive [[iodine]] were found in the [[breast milk]] of women living east of Tokyo. However, the levels were below the safety limits for tap water consumption by infants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/national/view/small-amounts-of-radioactive-iodine-found-in-breast-milk |title=Small amounts of radioactive iodine found in breast milk of 4 women |publisher=Japan Today |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=16 May 2011}}</ref>  Regulatory limits for infants in Japan are several levels of magnitude beneath what is known to potentially affect human health{{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}. Radiation protection standards in Japan are currently stricter than international recommendations and the standards of most other states, including those in North America and Europe .<ref>http://www.japanprobe.com/2011/12/27/japans-new-limits-for-radiation-in-food-20-times-stricter-than-american-and-eu-standards/</ref> By Nov 2012, no radioactivity was detected in Fukushimas mothers breast milk. 100% of samples contained no detectable amount of radiation.<ref>http://ajw.asahi.com/article/0311disaster/fukushima/AJ201211060058</ref><ref>http://fukushima.greenaction-japan.org/2012/11/13/no-radioactivity-found-in-fukushima-mothers-breast-milk/</ref>

====Baby-milk====
Mid November 2011 radioactive cesium was found in milk-powder for baby-food produced by the food company [[Meiji Dairies|Meiji Co.]] Although this firm was warned about this matter three times, the matter was only taken seriously by its consumer service after it was approached by [[Kyodo News]]. Up to 30.8 becquerels per kilogram was found in Meiji Step milk powder. While this is under the governmental safety-limit of 200 becquerels per kilogram, this could be more harmful for young children. Because of this cesium-contaminated milk powder, the Japanese minister of health Yoko Komiyama said on 9 December 2011 at a press conference, that her ministry would start regularly tests on baby food products in connection with the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear plant crisis, every three months and more frequently when necessary. Komiyama said: "As mothers and other consumers are very concerned (about radiation), we want to carry out regular tests", Test done by the government in July and August 2011 on 25 baby products did not reveal any contamination.<ref>The Mainichi Daily News (10 December 2011) [http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20111209p2g00m0dm174000c.html Meiji ignored info on cesium-tainted baby food for 2 weeks]</ref>

====Children====
In a survey by the local and central governments conducted on 1,080 children aged 0 to 15 in Iwaki, Kawamata and Iitate on 26<U+2013>30 March, almost 45 percent of these children had experienced [[thyroid]] exposure to radiation with radioactive [[iodine]], although in all cases the amounts of radiation did not warrant further examination, according to the [[Japanese Nuclear Safety Commission|Nuclear Safety Commission]] on Tuesday 5 July. In October 2011, [[hormone|hormonal]] irregularies in 10 evacuated children were reported. However, the organization responsible for the study said that no link had been established between the children's condition and explosure to radiation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20111004p2g00m0dm116000c.html |title=Thyroid gland irregularities found in young evacuees from Fukushima |publisher=The Manichi Daily News |date=4 October 2011 |accessdate=14 October 2011}}</ref>

On 9 October a survey started in the prefecture Fukushima: ultrasonic examinations were done of the thyroid glands of all 360.000 children between 0 to 18 years of age. Follow-up tests will be done for the rest of their lives. This was done in response to concerned parents, alarmed by the evidence showing increased incidence of thyroid cancer among children after the 1986 Chernobyl disaster. The project was done by the Medical University of Fukushima.<ref>Kyodo-news(9 October 2011)[http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2011/10/119366.html Fukushima children start undergoing lifelong thyroid examinations]</ref> The results of the tests will be mailed to the children within a month. At the end of 2014 the initial testing of all children should be completed, after this the children will undergo a thyroid checkup every 2 years until they turn 20, and once every 5 years above that age.<ref>JIAF(9 October 2011)[http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1318217190P.pdf Earthuake-report 230: Thyroid checkups begin for Fukushima children]</ref>

In November 2011 in urine-samples of 1500 pre-school-children (ages 6 years or younger) from the city of [[Minamisoma]] in the prefecture Fukushima radioactive cesium was found in 104 cases. Most had levels between 20 and 30 becquerels per liter, just above the detection limit, but 187 becquerels was found in the urine of a one-year-old baby boy. All was done because the parents were afraid for internal exposure. Local governments only covered the tests for elementary schoolchildren and older students. According to RHC JAPAN a medical consultancy firm in Tokyo, these levels could not harm the health of the children. But director Makoto Akashi of the National Institute of Radiological Sciences said, that although those test results should be verified, this still proved the possibility of internal exposure in the children of Fukushima, but that the internal exposure would not increase, when all food was tested for radioactivity before consumption.<ref>NHK-world (5 November 2011) [http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/05_07.html  Radioactivity in Fukushima children's urine]</ref><ref>JAIF (5 November 2011) [http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1320469975P.pdf Earthquake-report 256]</ref>

====Soil====
Also in July citizens groups reported that a survey of soil at four places in the city of Fukushima taken on 26 June proved that all samples were contaminated with radioactive caesium, measuring 16,000 to 46,000 becquerels per kilogram and exceeding the legal limit of 10,000 becquerels per kg,<ref>''Kyodo-news'' (5 July 2011) [http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2011/07/101083.html 45% of kids in Fukushima survey had thyroid exposure to radiation]</ref> A study published by the [[PNAS]] found that [[cesium 137]] had 'strongly contaminated the soils in large areas of eastern and northeastern Japan'<ref>{{cite web|author=Edward Calabrese |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/early/2011/11/11/1112058108 |title=Cesium-137 deposition and contamination of Japanese soils due to the Fukushima nuclear accident |publisher=Pnas.org |date= |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref>

====Wildlife====
After the find of 28,000 [[becquerel]]s of [[caesium]] per kilogram in wild [[mushroom]]s, and a [[wild boar]] that was found with radiation amounts about 6 times the safety limit, Professor Yasuyuki Muramatsu at the [[Gakushuin University]] urged detailed checks on wild plants and animals. Radioactive caesium in soil and fallen leaves in forests in his opinion would be easily absorbed by mushrooms and edible plants. He said that wild animals like boars were bound to accumulate high levels of radiation by eating contaminated mushrooms and plants. The professor added that detailed studies were needed on wild plants and animals. Across Europe the [[Chernobyl]]-incident had likewise effects on wild fauna and flora.<ref>JAIF (12 September 2011) [http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1315808560P.pdf Earthquake report 202: Radiation checks on wild plants, animals urged]</ref>
The first study of the effects of radioactive contamination following the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster demonstrated through standard point count censuses that the abundance of birds was negatively correlated with radioactive contamination, and that among the 14 species in common between the Fukushima and the Chernobyl regions, the decline in abundance was steeper in Fukushima.<ref>
{{Cite journal
| issn =  0269-7491
| volume = 164
| pages = 36<U+2013>39
| last = M<U+00F8>ller
| first = A P
| coauthors = A Hagiwara, S Matsui, S Kasahara, K Kawatsu, I Nishiumi, H Suzuki, K Ueda, T A Mousseau
| title = Abundance of birds in Fukushima as judged from Chernobyl
| journal = Environmental Pollution
| accessdate =24 February 2012
| year = 2012
| doi = 10.1016/j.envpol.2012.01.008
}}
</ref> 

Scientists in [[Alaska]] are testing [[Pinniped|seal]]s struck with an unknown illness to see if it is connected to radiation from Fukushima.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/45800485/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/scientists-test-sick-alaska-seals-radiation/#.TwV9ojVOAcU |title=Scientists test sick Alaska seals for radiation - Technology & science - Science - msnbc.com |publisher=MSNBC |date=27 December 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> 
Japanese bloggers are also reporting sick birds that cannot fly in the Fukushima area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ex-skf.blogspot.com/2012/01/video-of-birds-that-dont-fly-in-june.html |title=Video of Birds That Don't Fly, in June 2011 Somewhere in Fukushima &#124; EXSKF |publisher=Ex-skf.blogspot.com |date=4 January 2012 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref>

About a year after the nuclear disaster scientists found mutated butterflies. This was an unexpected finding, as they believe <U+201C>insects are very resistant to radiation.<U+201D> Since these are recent findings, the study suggests that these mutations have been passed down from older generations. Additionally, they found radioactive fish, such as tuna, in Japanese waters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-202_162-57492524/report-mutated-butterflies-found-near-fukushima/ |author=CBS News |title=Report: Mutated butterflies found near Fukushima |date=August 13, 2012.}}</ref>

====Plankton====
Radioactive cesium was found in high concentration in plankton in the sea near the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant. Samples were taken up to 60 kilometers from the coast of [[Iwaki, Fukushima|Iwaki]] city in July 2011 by scientists of the [[Tokyo University]] of Marine Science and Technology. Up to 669 becquerels per kilogram of radioactive cesium was measured in samples of animal plankton taken 3 kilometers offshore. The leader of the research-group Professor Takashi Ishimaru, said that the sea current continuously carried contaminated water southwards from the plant. Further studies to determine the effect on the food-chain and fish would be needed.<ref>JAIF (15 October 2011)[http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1318651768P.pdf  Earthquake-report 235: Radioactive cesium found in plankton off the nuclear plant]</ref>

====Building materials====
Detectable levels of radiation were found in an apartment building in [[Nihonmatsu, Fukushima]], where the foundation was made using concrete containing crushed stone collected from a quarry near the troubled Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant, situated inside the evacuation-zone. Of the 12 households living there were 10 households relocated after the quake.<ref>The Mainichi Daily News) (21 January 2012)[http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20120121p2a00m0na014000c.html Radiation of 40 microsieverts per hour detected at Namie quarry]</ref> After inspection at the quarry <U+2013> situated inside the evacuation-zone around the nuclear plant<U+2014>in the town of [[Namie, Fukushima]] between 11 and 40 microsieverts of radiation per hour were detected one meter above gravel held at eight storage sites in the open, while 16 to 21 microsieverts were detected in three locations covered by roofs. From this place about 5,200 metric tons of gravel was shipped from this place and used as building material. On 21 January 2012 the association of quarry agents in the prefecture Fukushima asked its members to voluntarily check the radiation doses of their products to ease public concerns over radioactive contamination of building materials.<ref>The Mainichi Daily News (21 January 2012)[http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20120121p2g00m0dm011000c.html Fukushima quarry agents to voluntarily check radiation level]</ref> The minister of Industry Yukio Edano did instruct TEPCO to pay compensation for the economical damages. Raised radiation levels were found on many buildings constructed after the quake.<ref>The Mainichi Daily News (20 January 2012) [http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20120120p2g00m0dm177000c.html TEPCO urged to compensate for tainted building material in Fukushima]</ref> Schools, private houses, roads. Because of the public anger raised by these finds. the government of [[Nihonmatsu, Fukusima]] decided to examine all 224 city construction projects started after the quake.<ref>The Mainichi Daily News (20 January 2012)[http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20120120p2a00m0na009000c.html Radioactive gravel also used in construction of private house in Fukushima]</ref><ref>JAIF (20 January 2012)[http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1327033033P.pdf Earthquake report 323]</ref><ref>JAIF (21 January 2012)[http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1327123860P.pdf Earthquake report 324]</ref> Some 200 construction companies received stone from the Namie-quarry, and the material was used in at least 1000 building-sites. The contaminated stone was found in some 49 houses and apartments. Radiation-levels of 0.8 mSv per hour were found, almost as high as the radiation-levels outside the homes.<ref>JAIF (22 January 2012) [http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1327204022P.pdf Earthquake report 325: Contaminated crushed stone found in more houses]</ref><ref>NHK-world (21 January 2012) [http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/20120121_17.html Contaminated crushed stone found in more houses]</ref> None of these represents a potential danger to human health.{{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}

On 22 January 2012, the Japanese government survey had identified around 60 houses built with the radioactive contaminated concrete. Even after 12 April 2011, when the area was declared to be an evacuation zone, the shipments continued, and the stone was used for building purposes.<ref>The Mainichi Daily News (23 January 2012)[http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20120123p2g00m0dm017000c.html Radioactive crushed stone used in around 60 Fukushima buildings]</ref>

In the first weeks of February 2012 up to 214,200 becquerels of radioactive cesium per kilogram was measured in samples gravel in the quarry near Namie, situated inside the evacuation zone. The gravel stored outsite showed about 60,000<U+2013>210,000 becquerels of cesium in most samples. From the 25 quarries in the evacuation zones, up to 122,400 becquerels of radioactive cesium was found at one that has been closed since the nuclear crisis broke out on 11 March 2011. In one quarry, that is still operational 5,170 becquerels  per kilogram was found. Inspections were done at some 150 of the 1.100 construction sites, where the gravel form the Namie-quarry was supected to be used. At 27 locations the radioation levels were higher than the surrounding area.<ref>The Mainichi Daily News (16 February 2012)[http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20120216p2a00m0na006000c.html Massive levels of radioactive cesium detected at quarry near Fukushima plant]</ref>

===Hot spots at school-yards===
On 6 May 2012 it became known that according to documents of the municipal education board reports submitted by each school in Fukushima prefecture in April at least  14 elementary schools, 7 junior high and 5 nursery schools so called "hot spots" existed, where the radiation exposure was more than 3.8 microsieverts per hour, resulting in an annual cummulative dose above 20 millisieverts. However all restrictions, that limited the maximum time to three hours for the children to play outside at the playgrounds of the schools, were lifted at the beginning of the new academic year in April by the education board. The documents were obtained by a group of civilians after a formal request to disclose the information. Tokiko Noguchi, the foreman of a group of civilians, insisted that the education board would restore the restrictions.<ref>The Mainichi Shimbun (7 May 2012)[http://mainichi.jp/english/english/newsselect/news/20120507p2g00m0dm041000c.html 'Hot spots' detected at more than 20 schools in Koriyama]</ref>

====New radiation limits for food in Japan====
On 22 December 2011 the Japanese government announced new limits for radioactive cesium in food. The new norms would be enforced in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nakamura|first=Tsuyoshi|title=New radiation limits alarm local entities|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T111224002468.htm|publisher=Daily Yomiuri Online|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>

{| style="margin-left:40px;"
|-
| '''food''' || '''new norm''' ||  '''old limit'''
|-
| rice, meat, vegetables, fish|| 100 becquerel per kilogram|| 500 becquerel per kilogram
|-
| milk, milk-powder, infant-food || 50 becquerel per kilogram || 200 becquerel per kilogram
|-
| drinking water || 10 becquerel per liter || 200 becquerel per liter
|}

On 31 March 2012 the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare of Japan published a report on radioactive cesium found in food. Between January and around 15 March 2012 at 421 occasions food was found containing more than 100 becquerels per kilogram cesium. All was found within 8 prefectures: [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]], [[Fukushima Prefecture|Fukushima]] (285 finds), [[Gunma Prefecture|Gunma]], [[Ibaraki prefecture|Ibaraki]] (36 finds), [[Iwate Prefecture|Iwate]], [[Miyagi Prefecture|Miyagi]], [[Tochigi Prefecture|Tochigi]] (29 finds) and [[Yamagata prefecture|Yamagata]]. Most times it involved fish: landlocked salmon and flounder, seafood, after this: Shiitake-mushrooms or the meat of wild animals.<ref>The Mainichi Shimbun (1 April 2012) [http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20120401p2g00m0dm012000c.html Foods with excessive radiation under new rule found in 8 prefectures]</ref><ref>NHK-world (1 April 2012)[http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/20120401_12.html Government tightens control over cesium in food]</ref>

In the first week of April 2012 cesium-contamination above legal limits was found in:
* Shiitake mushrooms in [[Manazuru]] [[Kanagawa prefecture]] situated at 300 kilometers from Fukushima: 141 becquerels/kg
* bamboo-shoots in two cities in [[Chiba prefecture]]
* bamboo-shoots and Shiitake-mushrooms in 5 cities in the region [[Kant<U+014D> region|Kant<U+014D>]], [[Ibaraki prefecture]]
In [[Gunma]] prefecture 106 becquerels/kg was found in beef. Sharper limits for meat would be taken effect in October 2012, but in order to ease consumer concern the farmers were asked to refrain from shipping.<ref>JAIF (8 April 2012)[http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1333857057P.pdf Earthquake-report 397: Radioactive cesium found in farm goods near Tokyo]</ref>

==Decontamination efforts==
In the last week of August premier minister Naoto Kan informed the governor of Fukushima Prefecture about the plans to build a central storage facility to store and treat nuclear waste including contaminated soil in Fukushima. On 27 August at a meeting in Fukushima City Governor Yuhei Sato spoke out his concern about the sudden proposals, and the implications that this would have for the prefecture and its inhabitants, that already had endured so much from the nuclear accident. Kan said, that the government had no intention to make the plant a final facility, but the request was needed in order to make a start with decontamination.<ref>''Jaif'' (28 August 2011) [http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1314504467P.pdf Kan: Central storage plant planned in Fukushima]</ref>

==Distribution outside Japan==

Radiation from the disaster were found in [[kelp]] off of [[Coastal California]].<ref>[http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=radioactive-iodine-from-from-fukushima-found-in-california-kelp Radioactive Iodine from Fukushima Found in California Kelp] 30 March 2012</ref>

According to a Professor at Stanford, there were some metrological effects involved and that <U+201C>81 percent of all the emissions were deposited over the ocean<U+201D> instead of mainly being spread inland.<ref name="Jason Gale"/> Although they say levels are low, Researchers at the University of California at Berkeley have shown that there has been an increase in radiation along the west coast of North America. Berkeley researchers measured San Francisco's rainwater radiation levels and found that <U+201C>San Francisco rain water radiation levels exceeded federal drinking water thresholds by as much as 181 times recently.<U+201D> The rainwater is falling on crops and <U+201C>being ingested in cows, which have begun passing it through into their milk and radioactivity has been detected.<U+201D> <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/san-francisco-rainwater-radiation-181-times-above-us-drinking-water-standard-2011-4 |author=DK Matai |title=San Francisco Rainwater: Radiation 181 Times Above US Drinking Water Standard |publisher=Business Insider |date=April 4, 2011.}}</ref>

===Distribution by sea===
Seawater containing measurable levels of iodine-131 and caesium-137 were collected by Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology (JAMSTEC) on 22<U+2013>23 March at several points 30&nbsp;km from the coastline iodine concentrations were "at or above Japanese regulatory limits" while caesium was "well below those limits" according to an IAEA report on 24 March.<ref name=IAEAiodine/> On 25 March, IAEA indicated that in the long term, caesium-137 (with a half-life of 30 years) would be the most relevant isotope as far as doses was concerned and indicated the possibility "to follow this nuclide over long distances for several years." The organization also said it could take months or years for the isotope to reach "other shores of the Pacific".<ref name=IAEAiodine/>
The survey by the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology (JAMSTEC) reveals that radioactive cesium released from Fukushima I Nuclear Power Plant reached the ocean 2000 kilometers from the plant and 5000 meters deep one month after the accident. It is considered that airborne cesium particles fell on the ocean surface, and sank as they were attached to the bodies of dead plankton. The survey result was announced in a symposium held on 20 November in Tokyo. From  18 to 30 April, JAMSTEC collected "marine snow", sub-millimeter particles made mostly of dead plankton and sand, off the coast of Kamchatka Peninsula, 2000 kilometers away from Fukushima, and off the coast of Ogasawara Islands, 1000 kilometers away, at 5000 meters below the ocean surface. The Agency detected radioactive cesium in both locations, and from the ratio of cesium-137 and cesium-134 and other observations it was determined that it was from Fukushima I Nuclear Power Plant. The density of radioactive cesium is still being analyzed, according to the Agency. It has been thus confirmed that radioactive materials in the ocean are moving and spreading not just by ocean currents but by various other means.

===Distribution by air===
[[File:Fukushima trajectory animation for days 10 to 21 after the accident.gif|thumb|File:Fukushima trajectory animation for days 10 to 21 after the accident]]
The United Nations predicted that the initial radiation [[Plume (hydrodynamics)|plume]] from the stricken Japanese reactors would reach the United States by 18 March. Health and nuclear experts emphasized that radiation in the plume would be diluted as it traveled and, at worst, would have extremely minor health consequences in the United States.<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/17/science/17plume.html?_r=1&hp Scientists Project Path of Radiation Plume] By William J. Broad, 16 March 2011, [[The New York Times]]</ref> A simulation by the Belgian Institute for Space Aeronomy indicated that trace amounts of radioactivity would reach California and Mexico around 19 March.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nouvelle simulation du nuage de pollution radioactive au Japon|date=16 March 2011|url=http://aeronomie.be/multimedia/video/daiichi3-washout_bira-iasb_animated.gif}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zamg.ac.at/aktuell/index.php?seite=1&artikel=ZAMG_2011-03-15GMT08:26 |title=Aktuelle Informationen |publisher=ZAMG |accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref> These predictions were tested by a worldwide network of highly sensitive radiative isotope measuring equipment, with the resulting data used to assess any potential impact to human health as well as the status of the reactors in Japan.<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/03/science/03meltdown.html From Afar, a Vivid Picture of Japan Crisis]</ref><ref>[http://www.epa.gov/radiation/rert/radnet-data-map.html US EPA Radnet Monitoring System Webpage]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref> Consequently, by 18 March [[Nuclear fallout|radioactive fallout]] including isotopes of iodine-131, iodine-132, tellurium-132, iodine-133, caesium-134 and caesium-137 was detected in air filters at the University of Washington, [[Seattle]], USA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fission Products in Seattle Reveal Clues about Japan Nuclear Disaster|date=25 March 2011|url=http://www.technologyreview.com/blog/arxiv/26571/|publisher=Technology Review, MIT}}</ref><ref>{{cite arxiv|eprint=1103.4853|title=Arrival time and magnitude of airborne fission products from the Fukushima, Japan, reactor incident as measured in Seattle, Washington, USA|date=24 March 2011|author = J. Diaz Leon, J. Kaspar, A. Knecht, M. L. Miller, R. G. H. Robertson, A. G. Schubert}}</ref>

Due to an [[anticyclone]] south of Japan{{Verify source|date=May 2011}}, favorable westerly winds were dominant during most of the first week of the accident, depositing most of the radioactive material out to sea and away from population centers, with some unfavorable wind directions depositing radioactive material over Tokyo. [[Low-pressure area]] over Eastern Japan gave less favorable wind directions 21<U+2013>22 March. Wind shift to north takes place Tuesday midnight. After the shift, the plume would again be pushed out to the sea for the next becoming days{{Clarify|date=May 2011}}. Roughly similar prediction results are presented for the next 36 hours by the Finnish Meteorological Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.ilmatieteenlaitos.fi/japan|work=Finnish Meteorological Institute|date=19 March 2011<!-- 09:39&nbsp;am UTC, 20 March 07:06&nbsp;am and 21 March 09:43&nbsp;pm-->|title=Forecast of air movement}}</ref> In spite of winds blowing towards Tokyo during 21<U+2013>22 March, he{{Who|date=May 2011}} comments, "From what I've been able to gather from official reports of radioactivity releases from the Fukushima plant, Tokyo will not receive levels of radiation dangerous to human health in the coming days, should emissions continue at current levels."{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}

[[Norwegian Institute for Air Research]] have continuous forecasts of the radioactive cloud and its movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transport.nilu.no/products/fukushima |title=Fukushima <U+2013> Atmospheric Transport |publisher=Transport.nilu.no |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref> These are based on the [[FLEXPART]] model, originally designed for forecasting the spread of radioactivity from the [[Chernobyl disaster]].

As of 28 April, the Washington State Department of Health, one of the U.S. states nearest Japan, reported that levels of radioactive material from the Fukushima plant had dropped significantly, and were now often below levels that could be detected with standard tests.<ref>[http://www.doh.wa.gov/Publicat/2011_news/11-064.htm Radioactive material in the state air from Japan nuclear reactors way down]</ref>

==Response in other countries==
{{see also|International reaction to the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster}}

===Rush for iodine===
[[File:IodineDistJapan.jpg|thumb|right|Packaged potassium iodide tablets.]]
Fear of radiation from Japan prompted a global rush for iodine pills, including in the United States,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hurd |first=Rick |title=Amid Japan nuclear drama, Bay Area potassium iodide sales skyrocket |work=[[Contra Costa Times]] |publisher=[[San Jose Mercury News]] |date=17 March 2011 |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_17631165?source=most_viewed&nclick_check=1 |accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref> Canada, Russia,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Radiation fears spark rush for iodine pills |work=CTV News |publisher=[[CTV Television Network]] |location=Canada |date=15 March 2011 |url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/TopStories/20110315/japan-radiation-iodine-pills-110315/ |accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref> Korea,<ref>{{Cite news |title=South Korean radiation fear iodine rush |publisher=Australia Network News |url=
http://australianetworknews.com/stories/201103/3166601.htm?desktop |accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref> China,<ref name="autogenerated14">{{Cite news |author=Jo Ling Kent |title=Chinese scramble to buy salt as radiation fears grow |publisher=CNN |date=17 March 2011 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/03/17/china.salt.scramble/# |accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref> Malaysia<ref name="heraldsun1">{{Cite news |title=Health experts warning over iodine rush |work=Herald Sun |location=Australia |date=15 March 2011<!-- 11:38&nbsp;pm --> |url=
http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/breaking-news/health-experts-warning-over-iodine-rush/story-e6frf7jx-1226022126886 |accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref> and Finland.<ref name="helsinginsanomat">{{cite web|title=Finnish nuclear authority investigates problems in online reporting on Japan |publisher=Helsingin Sanomat |location=Finland |date=15 March 2011 |url=
http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Finnish+nuclear+authority+investigates+problems+in+online+reporting+on+Japan+/1135264600262 |accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref> There is a rush for iodized salt in China.<ref name="autogenerated14"/> A rush for iodine antiseptic solution appeared in Malaysia. [[WHO]] warned against consumption of iodine pills without consulting a doctor and also warned against drinking iodine antiseptic solution.<ref name="heraldsun1"/> The United States Pentagon said troops are receiving [[potassium iodide]] before missions to areas where possible radiation exposure is likely.<ref>{{Cite news |title=U.S. to send drones over damaged nuke plant |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=16 March 2011 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503543_162-20044023-503543.html?tag=stack |accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref>

The World Health Organisation (WHO) says it has received reports of people being admitted to poison centres around the world after taking iodine tablets in response to fears about harmful levels of radiation coming out of the damaged nuclear power plant in Fukushima.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Worldwide reports of iodine overdoses: WHO |work=[[ABC Online]] |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=18 March 2011 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2011/03/18/3168067.htm |accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref>

===U.S. military===
{{See also| Operation Tomodachi }}
[[File:US Navy 110317-O-9999O-442 Senior Airman Eva Gaus, left, and Senior Airman Jonathan Jones indicate all clear to the pilot after checking beta and g.jpg|thumb|right|Humanitarian flight is checked for radiation at Yokota]]
In [[Operation Tomodachi]], the United States Navy dispatched the aircraft carrier {{USS|Ronald Reagan|CVN-76|6}} and other vessels in the [[Seventh Fleet]] to fly a series of helicopter operations.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.stripes.com/news/relief-efforts-still-getting-started-days-after-earthquake-1.137703|title = Relief efforts still getting started days after earthquake|publisher=Stripes.com| accessdate =15 March 2011}}</ref> A U.S. military spokesperson said that low-level radiation forced a change of course en route to Sendai.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dawson|first=Chester |title=WSJ online U.S. Military Joins in Quake-Relief Effort |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=14 March 2011 |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704893604576200183092822382.html |accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref> The ''Reagan'' and sailors aboard were exposed to "a month's worth of natural background radiation from the sun, rocks or soil"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Broad |first=William J. |title=Military Crew Said to Be Exposed to Radiation, but Officials Call Risk in U.S. Slight |newspaper=New York Times |date=13 March 2011 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/14/world/asia/14plume.html |accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref> in an hour and the carrier was repositioned.<ref>{{cite news|http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=212057|title=US aircraft carrier reportedly sails into radioactive cloud|work=[[Jerusalem Post]]|date=14 March 2011}}</ref> Seventeen sailors were decontaminated after they and their three helicopters were found to have been exposed to low levels of radioactivity.<ref>{{cite news|author=Shanker, Thom|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/14/world/asia/14military.html|title=17 in U.S. Navy Treated for Contamination|work=New York Times|date=14 March 2011}}</ref>

The aircraft carrier {{USS|George Washington|CVN-73|6}} was docked for maintenance at [[United States Fleet Activities Yokosuka|Yokosuka Naval Base]], about {{convert|280|km|mi}} from the plant, when instruments detected radiation at 07:00 JST on 15 March.<ref>{{Cite news|author=CNN Wire Staff|title=U.S. Navy aircraft carrier detects radiation|publisher=CNN|date=15 March 2011|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/03/15/japan.us.navy.radiation/|accessdate=15 March 2011}}</ref> Rear Admiral Richard Wren stated that the nuclear crisis in Fukushima, {{convert|320|km|mi}} from Yokosuka, was too distant to warrant a discussion about evacuating the base.<ref>Erik Slavin. ''Stars and Stripes'', 14 March 2011.</ref> Daily monitoring and some precautionary measures were recommended for Yokosuka and [[Atsugi]] bases, such as limiting outdoor activities and securing external ventilation systems.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2011/03/15/japanese-nuclear-panic-rises-agency-says-radiation-leaking-atmosphere/|title=Nuclear Officials May Spray Japanese Power Plant With Water by Helicopter|publisher=Fox News|date=15 March 2011}}</ref> As a precaution, the ''Washington'' was pulled out of its Yokosuka port later in the week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/03/21/japan.nuclear.reactors/?hpt=T2|work=CNN|title=Smoke spews from 2 reactors at stricken Japanese nuclear plant|date=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kztv10.com/news/uss-george-washington-leaves-port-in-japan/|title=USS George Washington Leaves Port In Japan|work=KZTV|date=21 March 2011}}</ref> The Navy also temporarily stopped moving its personnel to Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/03/navy-stop-movement-sailors-japan-031711w/|title=Navy stops moving sailors to Japan|date=17 March 2011|work=[[Army Times]]}}</ref>

==Isotopes of concern==
{{see also|Nuclear fission product#Countermeasures against the worst fission products found in incident fallout}}
The isotope [[iodine-131]] is easily absorbed by the [[thyroid]]. Persons exposed to releases of I-131 from any source have a higher risk for developing [[thyroid cancer]] or thyroid disease, or both. Iodine-131 has a short [[half-life]] at approximately 8 days, and therefore is an issue mostly in the first weeks after the incident. Children are more vulnerable to I-131 than adults. Increased risk for thyroid [[neoplasm]] remains elevated for at least 40 years after exposure. [[Potassium iodide]] tablets prevent iodine-131 absorption by saturating the thyroid with non-radioactive iodine.<ref name=Atsdr1>{{cite web |title=Radiation Exposure from Iodine 131: Physiologic Effects |publisher=[[Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry]] |location=United States |date=5 November 2002 |url=
http://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/csem/iodine/physiologic_effects.html |accessdate=21 March 2011}}</ref> Japan's Nuclear Safety Commission recommended local authorities to instruct evacuees leaving the 20-kilometre area to ingest stable (not radioactive) iodine.<ref name=IAEAiodine/> [[CBS News]] reported that the number of doses of potassium iodide available to the public in Japan was inadequate to meet the perceived needs for an extensive radioactive contamination event.<ref name=cbs3>{{Cite news |last=Millstone |first=Ken |title=Expert: Japan botching crisis management, iodine distribution |work=World Watch |publisher=CBS News |date=16 March 2011 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503543_162-20043836-503543.html?tag=contentMain;contentBody |accessdate=21 March 2011}}</ref>

[[Caesium-137]] is also a particular threat because it behaves like [[potassium]] and is taken up by cells throughout the body. Additionally, it has a long, 30-year half-life.<ref>http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caesium-137#Radioactive_caesium_in_the_environment Radioactive caesium in the environment

Wikipedia</ref>  Cs-137 can cause acute [[radiation sickness]], and increase the risk for cancer because of exposure to high-energy gamma radiation. Internal exposure to Cs-137, through ingestion or inhalation, allows the radioactive material to be distributed in the soft tissues, especially muscle tissue, exposing these tissues to the beta particles and gamma radiation and increasing cancer risk.<ref name=CDC1>{{cite web |title=Radioisotope Brief: Cesium-137 (Cs-137) |work=Emergency Preparedness and Response |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |location=United States |date=18 August 2004 |url=
http://www.bt.cdc.gov/radiation/isotopes/cesium.asp |accessdate=21 March 2011}}</ref>  [[Prussian blue]] helps the body excrete caesium-137.<ref name=cbs3/><ref name=Atsdr2>[http://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/toxprofiles/tp157.pdf Toxicological profile for caesium] [[Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry]], April 2004</ref>

[[Strontium-90]] behaves like [[calcium]], and tends to deposit in bone and blood-forming tissue (bone marrow). 20<U+2013>30% of ingested Sr-90 is absorbed and deposited in the bone. Internal exposure to Sr-90 is linked to bone cancer, cancer of the soft tissue near the bone, and leukemia.<ref name=epa1>[http://www.epa.gov/rpdweb00/radionuclides/strontium.html#affecthealth Strontium] [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]</ref> Risk of cancer increases with increased exposure to Sr-90.<ref name="epa1"/><ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite journal | title = Stealthy, silent destroyer of DNA | journal=[[The Australian]] | date = 16 March 2011 | first = Adam | last = Cresswell | postscript = <!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to "." for the cite to end in a ".", as necessary. -->{{inconsistent citations}}}}</ref>

[[Plutonium]] is also present in the [[MOX fuel]] of the Unit 3 reactor and in spent fuel rods.<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-11386_3-20042852-76.html Plutonium threat at Japan reactor, expert warns] 14 March 2011, Cnet News</ref> Officials at the International Atomic Energy Agency say the presence of MOX fuel does not add significantly to the dangers. [[Plutonium-239]] is particularly long-lived and toxic with a half-life of 24,000 years and remains hazardous for tens of thousands of years.<ref name=npr1>[http://www.npr.org/2011/03/16/134600825/plutonium-in-fuel-rods-cause-for-concern?ps=cprs Plutonium In Fuel Rods: Cause For Concern?] By Dan Charles, 17 March 2011, NPR.</ref> Radioactive products with a long half-life are less radioactive then products with a short half life, as isotopes with a long half life emit particles extremely rarely. Experts commented that the long-term risk associated with [[Plutonium#Toxicity|plutonium toxicity]] is "highly dependent on the [[geochemistry]] of the particular site."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hlkw9Naz9zbM-lkEkbSNZMaTjCIQ?docId=CNG.c1d5ac807748f7defd76c46d8c484e61.641 |title=Japan lacking radioactive water storage: US experts |publisher=Google.com |date=28 March 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref>

